The PEC measurements were taken in 0.5 M Na2SO4 aqueous solution (pH 5.6) using a conventional three-electrode electrochemical workstation equipped with a working electrode, counter electrode (Pt foil (1.6 cm2)), and Ag/AgCl in a 3 M KCl solution (EAg/AgCl) as the reference electrode. The working photoelectrodes were produced on Fluorine-doped tin oxide (FTO) coated glass. All measured EAg/AgCl
                         was reported in terms of the reversible hydrogen electrode (ERHE
                        ) by the Nernst equation. A 400 W metal halide lamp (Osram, HQI-BT 400 W/D PRO) with an adjusted intensity equal to 100 mW cm−2 (AM 1.5 G) and an ultraviolet cutoff filter (λ < 400 nm) were used as the light source.

It was remarkable that the ηsep, ηinj
                        , and PL (as shown in Fig. 7b, 7c, and 7d, respectively) are drastically decreased in the BaV/Ag (15 nm)/Ag@TG photoanodes in which Ag was inserted a between the layers with a thickness of 15 nm using PVD method. This result confirms the importance of the connection BaV and Ag@TG and the role of Ag in improving of this interconnection. In other words, achieving an indirect Z-scheme system requires not only suitable band alignment between semiconductors and the presence of a mediator, but also a good contact between them. Therefore, it is essential to optimize the amount of Ag insertion to achieve a good contact. As mentioned earlier, the best result in this work was obtained when the Ag loading was performed by spin-coating 20 μl from 0.001 mol NPs suspension (see Figs. 7 and S8
                        ).
